  <h1>Wrongful Death Statute of Limitations by State</h1>
  <p class="byline">By Sutton Hardwick, Contributing Writer. Reviewed May 2026.</p>

  <p>Statutes of limitations for wrongful death claims are shorter and less forgiving than survivors typically expect. Missing the deadline is fatal to the claim &mdash; the case is dismissed and the right to recovery is gone. This guide covers state-by-state deadlines and the most common exceptions.</p>

  <h2>The general rule</h2>
  <p>Most states give 2 years from the date of death to file a wrongful death claim. Some give 1 year (notably Kentucky, Louisiana, Tennessee). Some give 3 years (Massachusetts, North Dakota). A handful follow other patterns.</p>
  <p>The clock typically starts on the <em>date of death</em>, not the date of injury. If the decedent was injured on May 1, 2024 and died on August 15, 2024, the wrongful death clock starts August 15, 2024 in most states. (The survival action, which covers pre-death damages, may have a different clock running from the injury date.)</p>

