  <h2>Common exceptions and shortening rules</h2>

  <h3>Medical malpractice deaths</h3>
  <p>Most states have separate, shorter limitations periods for medical malpractice wrongful death claims, often combined with a "statute of repose" that establishes an absolute outer limit (e.g., 4 or 6 years from the malpractice itself, regardless of when the death occurred or when the malpractice was discovered).</p>

  <h3>Government defendants</h3>
  <p>Claims against state, local, or federal government typically require pre-suit notice within a very short period &mdash; often 6 months, sometimes as short as 60 or 90 days. Failure to give timely notice bars the suit even if the underlying statute of limitations has not run. Examples: claims against police, public hospitals, school districts, transit authorities, federal employees (FTCA &mdash; Federal Tort Claims Act).</p>

  <h3>Discovery rule</h3>
  <p>In some cases the cause of death may not be apparent at the time. Asbestos or other toxic exposure cases, latent medical errors, defective products with delayed failure modes. Some states apply a "discovery rule" that delays the start of the clock until the cause of death is or should reasonably have been discovered. Other states do not apply it; the clock starts at death regardless.</p>

  <h3>Minor beneficiaries</h3>
  <p>If a beneficiary is a minor, some states toll the statute as to that beneficiary until they reach the age of majority. But this typically does not toll the entire claim &mdash; the personal representative or other beneficiaries with capacity still have to file within the regular deadline. The minor's tolling protects their share, not the timely filing requirement.</p>

  <h3>Fraudulent concealment</h3>
  <p>If a defendant fraudulently concealed information that would have alerted the survivors to the cause of action, the statute may be tolled. High bar; difficult to invoke.</p>

  <h3>Continuing representation</h3>
  <p>In medical malpractice cases where the negligent provider continued treating the decedent, the statute may not start until the treatment relationship ends. State-specific.</p>

  <h2>What to do immediately</h2>
  <p>Within the first 2 weeks of a death that may have been caused by another's negligence:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Talk to a wrongful death attorney.</strong> Initial consultations are typically free.</li>
    <li><strong>Preserve evidence.</strong> Police reports, medical records, scene photographs, witness contact information, any video.</li>
    <li><strong>Begin probate administration</strong> if your state requires a personal representative to bring the claim.</li>
    <li><strong>Calendar the deadline</strong> and treat it as inviolate.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>For the standing rules that determine who actually files, see <a href="/guides/who-can-file-a-wrongful-death-claim">who can file</a>. For what's recoverable when the claim is timely filed, see <a href="/guides/economic-damages-in-wrongful-death-cases">economic damages</a> and <a href="/guides/non-economic-damages-in-wrongful-death">non-economic damages</a>.</p>
